    Chinese AV&amp;quot;character'; this is the same word as Japanese 3 Throughout this paper we shall give Chinese examples in traditional orthography, followed by a Romanization into the scheme; numerals following each pinyin syllable represent tones.
    Examples will usually be accompanied by a translation, plus a morpheme-by-morpheme gloss given in parentheses whenever the translation does not adequately serve this purpose.
    In the pinyin transliterations a dash (-) separates syllables that may be considered part of the same phonological word; spaces are used to separate plausible phonological words; and a plus sign (4-) is used, where relevant, to indicate morpheme boundaries of interest.
